Analyst Takeaways Token 2049 / Solana Breakpoint

Dylan Bane

Sep 26, 2024 ⋅  10 min read

Last week, Singapore hosted both Token 2049 and Breakpoint.

Our Enterprise Research Analyst, Dylan Bane, shared his research insights throughout the conferences and gathered intel on what’s next for the industry.

Below are his Token 2049 and Solana Breakpoint takeaways.

The New Kids on the Block: DePIN and AI

The rising momentum of both DePIN and Crypto x AI over the last year and a half continued in Singapore.

AI had over 119 related side events, and DePIN had at least 60 dedicated side events throughout the week. With such a high volume of events, we saw event themes reach a striking granularity from Decentralized Energy to DePIN x AI to DePIN in Asia. The highest-level takeaway is that a lot is happening in these sectors. From innovation in DeWi protocols to intensifying efforts in executing the promise of decentralized GPU compute networks, it’s clear that the industry is hard at work. DePIN and Crypto x AI are tackling problems across the board in both Traditional Physical Infrastructure (TradPi) and Web2.

While we covered most emerging trends in DePIN and AI at previous conferences this year, I wanted to highlight what stood out in Singapore.

All Eyes on Geodnet

Geodnet came up in nearly every conversation about promising DePIN projects throughout the week. Such attention is unusual at a relatively low $33 million circulating market cap and could point to the network outperforming the broader markets over the coming months.

What appears to be driving investor interest is Geodnet’s seemingly strong fundamentals. The protocol is generating about $1.2 million in ARR, yielding a 27.5x Market Cap/Revenue multiple compared to about a ~1000x multiple for DePIN as a whole. 80% of this revenue goes to buying and burning GEOD, accruing significant value to the token.

* Note - Data in Table is as of August 1st, 2024.

Geodnet is solving a real problem by deploying RTK stations globally to increase GPS accuracy by 100x to centimeter-level precision. Use cases range from enhancing map precision for games like Pokemon Go to overcoming positioning barriers for remote-controlled robots.

With the token not yet listed on major exchanges, professional investors may see an early opportunity in Geodnet before the broader market gains access. Such intense interest in Geodnet signals an emerging shift in crypto investment philosophy towards fundamental analysis and possibly suggests that the DePIN sector will be evaluated more on substantive value accrual than other crypto sectors have been in the past.

Stay tuned for a future Messari report on Geodnet.

Polygon’s Agglayer Integrates with IoTeX 2.0

Polygon’s Sandeep Naiwal and IoTeX’s Raullen Chai announced the integration during the DePIN-focused R3al World Summit side event. The integration allows DePINs building on IoTeX to access the Agglayer’s liquidity and enable cross-chain settlement for DePINs. While the announcement flew under the radar during a jam-packed week, further analysis and consideration are merited.

DePIN protocols seem to be settling on four types of underlying infrastructure.

  • General Purpose L1s - Solana, Ethereum, Polygon etc.
  • App-Specific Chains - Akash on Cosmos, etc.
  • DePIN Specific L1s - IoTeX, Peaq
  • Partnership Focused L2s - Base

*Note: Data is as of May 29, 2023. Does not include Partnership-Focused L2s. XNet and Soarchain have both migrated to Solana.

Over the last two years, Solana has become the preferred base layer destination for DePIN, with a large number of migrations to Solana (e.g., Helium, Render, Soarchain, XNet) and new projects building on the L1. As DePINs build on Solana, the platform acquires compounding network effects, with DePINs able to take advantage of shared liquidity, composability, and interoperability with other DePINs on Solana. Alternative infrastructure layers must offer compelling value propositions to compete with Solana.

The remaining options for where to build all offer specialized value propositions. L2s like Base attract DePINs due to the strong integrations offered by parent companies, such as Coinbase. App-Chains like Akash take advantage of the increased customizability afforded by Cosmos’ design. DePIN specific L1s offer strong partnerships, expertise, and infrastructure tailored for DePIN protocols.

Polygon recently lost XNet in a migration to Solana, suggesting that its value proposition might not be strong enough to retain DePIN protocols. In response, focusing on cross-chain interoperability that will allow DePINs to tap into users and liquidity across blockchains appears to be Polygon's new strategy. Acting as an aggregator for multiple blockchain use cases, rather than creating custom-tailored solutions can also help Polygon avoid spreading itself too thin. As for IoTeX, it stands to benefit by offering increased access to Ethereum ecosystem liquidity and users for DePINs building with IoTeX.

As DePIN becomes a premier crypto sector and potentially the greatest end-user of blockchain infrastructure, chains will need to focus their efforts on attracting DePIN projects. The battle for DePIN seems to be edging towards Solana’s robust L1 rather than cross-chain DePIN interoperability. IoTeX’s integration with the Agglayer could shift momentum in how DePINs are constructed.

Web2/Infra Founders Coming to DePIN to Solve Problems

An increasingly salient trend in DePIN is that founders from Web2 or the infrastructure world are leveraging DePIN as a unique solution to problems they face in their spaces.

What’s particularly interesting is the wide range of spaces being addressed with DePIN. Three examples whose stories came through in Singapore were Mawari, Blockcast, and DAWN.

Mawari:

Mawari is building a cloud rendering platform for AR and XR content delivery to 5G enabled devices. The platform renders AR content remotely, delivering the content to end users in real-time using the cloud. This removes the need for bulky VR headsets, as the compute does not need to be done locally.

The company was founded in 2017, graduating from the T-Mobile Accelerator and securing three patents over the years. Mawari did not have crypto or blockchain on its radar until relatively recently, as it struggled with optimizing its content delivery at the last mile. Mawari realized that it could lower latency and decrease costs for its streaming platform with DePIN. Using a decentralized network of GPUs, Mawari is best able to take advantage of edge computing, streaming its content rendered in real-time to devices near the closest network nodes. Use cases from real estate visualization to medical education can use the Mawari platform.

Built on Solana, Mawari is a clear example of crypto and DePIN providing a unique solution for a Web2 problem.

DAWN:

DAWN is a decentralized fixed-wireless network that provides multi-gigabit broadband internet connections at up to 100x lower prices than traditional ISPs to retail end-users. The company leverages a series of distribution nodes to transmit internet bandwidth downstream from Internet Exchanges (IX) and Data Centers to households.

DAWN emerges out of Andrena, a small-scale ISP operating in the New York metropolitan area. Founded in 2016, Andrena purchases wholesale internet bandwidth from Data Centers and passes along the savings from wholesale prices to end-users through its fixed-wireless broadband network. Currently, Andrena offers internet at about $30/month compared to $60-$100/month on average for comparable broadband internet plans.

While we’ve written extensively about DAWN, it’s worth highlighting that Andrena can scale its fixed-wireless network much faster using DePIN while passing even more savings to end-users in the long run. With DAWN, anyone can purchase the node hardware and cloud-native routers, outsourcing CapEx and OpEx from DAWN to network participants. The network can scale globally from day 1 with no capital coordination or fundraising limitations. Furthermore, DAWN creates more cost savings for retail users by allowing them to sell excess bandwidth to the network. As a result, the cost of a high-speed internet connection becomes nearly free for end-users.

DAWN arises from a successful web2 company in Andrena coming to DePIN to enhance the scalability and capital efficiency of its network.

Blockcast:

Blockcast is a content delivery network (CDN) leveraging multicast technology to increase access to high-quality internet bandwidth at a lower cost.

The founder of Blockcast, Omar, joined Facebook’s Connectivity Lab nearly ten years ago after the social media giant acquired an internet connectivity startup that Omar joined coming out of UC Berkeley. He was assigned to a team expanding internet connectivity near Lake Kivu in the East of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). There, they managed to expand access to SMS and voice calls, but faced challenges with providing access to data services that could enable video streaming services like Youtube or Netflix. Blockcast’s founder noticed that this problem was present not only in remote regions but also in airplanes and cruise ships, where inflight WiFi typically prevented video streaming due to backhaul issues.

Inspired by Helium, which managed to build a mobile network faster and cheaper than traditional ISPs using DePIN, Blockcast set out to build the Helium for CDNs. Using multicast technology, Blockcast allows anyone to host nodes that can provide video streaming capacity to nearby devices. The network is trustless and decentralized, rewarding node owners for their participation in the CDN chain. Due to its distributed nature, the network bypasses outage and performance issues through seamless rerouting to maximize performance and uptime. Furthermore, like DAWN, the network can scale faster and more efficiently as no central coordination or fundraising is required to expand CapEx and its operations.

Once again, with Blockcast we see a Web2 founder come to DePIN for a unique solution to a longstanding problem.

Solana Institutional Adoption

Beyond DePIN and AI-related takeaways, Solana quietly solidified itself as perhaps the prime target for the institutional adoption of blockchain.

At this time last year, Solana appeared among the least likely major chains for the eventual tokenization of RWAs and institutional adoption. Due to KYC laws and regulations, customizable sub-chains and L2s seemed like the best choices for institutions considering tokenization.

For example, Avalanche’s subnets and Polygon’s supernets enabled institutions to create semi-private chains adherent to regulations, which could still tap into the liquidity and functionality of their larger public parent chains. Avalanche saw success with its Evergreen institutional subnets, including tokenizing a $4 billion KKR healthcare private equity fund. Polygon saw Franklin Templeton tokenize a $400 million money market fund on its chain.

With concerns over the security of large transactions, Ethereum and its budding L2 ecosystem also seemed like a promising candidate for tokenization. Indeed, large companies like EY are building enterprise L2s on Ethereum.

Solana rejected a subnet-type framework, pushing for tokenization on its public L1. For risk-averse financial institutions, tokenizing on a public L1 appeared extreme compared to alternative options. Solana was not destined for institutional adoption in the eyes of many.

However, Solana has emerged as a prime player in the race for tokenization over the last six months. The primary reason appears to be Solana’s strength in enabling low-value transactions on-chain at scale.

The beginning of institutional adoption on Solana started just about a year ago when Visa partnered with the L1 to enable stablecoin settlement. In May, PayPal introduced PYUSD on Solana, a new stablecoin for the PayPal ecosystem. PayPal chose Solana due to its capacity for a high number of low-cost transactions.

Now, with Breakpoint 2024, we’re seeing an acceleration in the institutional adoption of Solana:

First, Franklin Templeton ($1.4 trillion AUM) announced that it is tokenizing a mutual fund for Solana.

Then, Citi Bank announced that it’s exploring Solana for cross-border financial transactions and smart contracts.

Demonstrated institutional trust in Solana bodes well for its future, as Ethereum’s prospects become increasingly shaky. If even the most conservative TradFi institutions are choosing Solana over the Ethereum ecosystem, the idea that Ethereum’s value proposition lies in its superior security and valuable real estate becomes increasingly questionable.
